{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Derive and enforce plan-material-pin health\n\n## Goal\nUse signed pins as the single related-material validity check across every attestation lifecycle consumer, while preserving safe rollout for existing projects.\n\n## Implementation\n- Register `enforce_plan_material_pins: bool = False` on `_config_schema.py::VerifyConfig` and add `\"enforce_plan_material_pins\": lambda v, k: _as_bool(v, k)` to `_SECTIONS[\"verify\"]`; the config-surface golden records the key. Add `_read_enforce_plan_material_pins(repo_root) -> bool` as the only read boundary for this optional key: after schema registration it reads `load_config().verify.enforce_plan_material_pins`, catches `ConfigError`, emits a structured `logger.warning` with event `plan_material_pin_config_unreadable`, and returns false. This is an intentional key-local fail-open rollout policy modeled on `mcp_readonly()`, not the general `verify.*` posture. A successfully parsed true value enforces all malformed/missing/drift outcomes fail-closed.\n- Own the nested `DerivedPlanReviewHealth` contract returned as `health` beside the existing `attest.compute_validity` top-level `{valid, reason, verdict}`. It has `pin_status` exactly `current`, `stale-pin-drift`, `stale-pin-missing`, `malformed-pin`, or `legacy-unpinned`; `enforced: bool`; and `targets: list[TargetPinDetail]`. Aggregate target status by fixed severity `malformed-pin > stale-pin-missing > stale-pin-drift > current`; `legacy-unpinned` occurs only for a wholly unpinned manifest with an empty targets list. Child 5967 extends the same contract with `phase_status` and phase compatibility after it introduces the phase manifest format. `TargetPinDetail` is exactly `{canonical_id: string, role: child|prerequisite, pinned_fingerprint: string, current_fingerprint: string|null, pin_status: current|stale-pin-drift|stale-pin-missing|malformed-pin}`. Compare pins against current narrow material to populate it; all renderers consume this contract rather than duplicating strings.\n- Add `derive_plan_material_pin_health(pin_records: Sequence[PlanMaterialPin] | None, *, repo_root, enforced)` in `attest.py`; `PlanMaterialPin` is child acaf's typed `{role, canonical_id, material_fingerprint}` record, and its `material_fingerprint` becomes `TargetPinDetail.pinned_fingerprint`. Callers pass `None` only when no field/manifest lines exist; `None` or an empty sequence produces `legacy-unpinned`. Add `sidecar.parse_reviewed_related_material(raw: object) -> tuple[PlanMaterialPin, ...] | None` for raw sidecar dictionaries; it returns `None` only for an absent field and raises `ReviewedRelatedMaterialError` for any present invalid list/item/key/role/ID/fingerprint/order/duplicate. Re-sign catches that exact error and returns malformed-pin without raising. The typed health helper resolves current target states without requiring a certified attestation. Missing/deleted targets produce `stale-pin-missing` silently. Canonical lookup ambiguity/mismatch maps to `failure_kind=resolution`; tracker/path/read/permission/OSError maps to `io`; reducer or narrow-fingerprint computation failure maps to `reducer`. Each non-absence failure emits structured warning `plan_material_pin_target_unreadable`, returns `stale-pin-missing` with `current_fingerprint=null`, and never raises. Aggregate in this helper by `malformed-pin > stale-pin-missing > stale-pin-drift > current`; `legacy-unpinned` is permitted only when the whole input is absent/empty, never per target. `compute_validity` invokes it after signature and plan-review-kind verification; re-sign invokes it after sidecar parsing.\n- When enabled, drift, malformed pins, or a deleted/missing pinned target invalidate the attestation. Archived targets remain readable. When disabled, report the same observations as advisory while `valid` remains true. Treat a wholly unpinned legacy attestation or pre-feature sidecar as valid in either mode. Do not rewrite signed pins when configuration changes.\n- Define `PlanValidityProfile` with exactly `DEFAULT`, `CLOSE`, and `DRIFT_REFRESH`. Extend the existing `attest.compute_validity(attestation, ticket_state, kind, *, repo_root=None, profile=PlanValidityProfile.DEFAULT)` without renaming or wrapping it. For `kind=completion-verifier` the profile is ignored and existing completion callers never parse pins. Keep the existing claim-gate → `compute_validity` and idempotent-reuse → claim-gate routing, and make their call chain explicitly select `profile=PlanValidityProfile.DEFAULT`; child 2bbd later wires `CLOSE` into `transition_close`, while child cb6b owns audit and UI rendering calls. `DEFAULT` runs every existing check including code freshness. `CLOSE` and `DRIFT_REFRESH` deliberately share one rule in this story—disable only code freshness—but remain distinct call-site intents so later close policy cannot silently change progressive refresh. Every other existing check, including reopen, signature, registry, own material, and configured pins, remains active. Child 5967 later adds phase compatibility to all profiles.\n- In `drift_refresh_candidate`, call `_reads.show_ticket(ticket_id, repo_root=repo_root)` and `signing.verify_signature`; any ticket read or signature exception returns `None`. Pass the resulting full `ticket_state` and verified attestation result to `compute_validity(kind=plan-review, profile=DRIFT_REFRESH)`. Remove the redundant inline signature, kind, registry, and own-material guards; an invalid result returns `None` before the probe. After a valid result, retain only dependency extraction/nonempty validation and the current-versus-signed dependency-hash comparison that proves code drift exists. This intentionally makes a reopen deny progressive refresh, matching all other plan-review validity consumers.\n- After signature certification and plan-review-kind validation, parse pins and build `DerivedPlanReviewHealth` before all reopen, registry, code, and own-material early returns; every such plan-review return includes `health`. This ordering intentionally pays the related-state read cost so audit/UI can diagnose simultaneous pin drift even when a cheaper existing invalidation controls the top-level verdict. Malformed pin syntax returns `malformed-pin` immediately. Otherwise existing verdict precedence is preserved, with health exposing simultaneous pin drift. When enforcement alone causes invalidity, verdict equals `stale-pin-drift`, `stale-pin-missing`, or `malformed-pin`; disabled enforcement keeps `verdict=certified` and exposes advisory health. Completion-verifier results retain their existing shape and omit health. Adding health to plan-review results is an additive internal interface change. Audit every current `compute_validity` caller: `claim_gate_check` and `drift_refresh_candidate` consume plan-review results by named key; `_attested_delivered` and `src/rebar/llm/completion.py` pass `kind=completion-verifier` and retain the three-key shape. Tests assert no current caller positionally unpacks or exact-shape validates a plan-review result. Rollback removes the additive health key and its consumers; no stored-data migration is required. If `DRIFT_REFRESH` delegation is defective, restore the removed inline signature/kind/registry/own-material guards from version control; this also requires no data migration.\n- In `_run_plan_review`, retain child acaf's pre-LLM `PlanRelationSnapshot` as local `review_snapshot`. On the full LLM path call `sidecar.emit(verdict, material=material, reviewed_related_material=review_snapshot.related_material, repo_root=repo_root)`. Extend `sidecar.emit` and `build_payload` with keyword-only `reviewed_related_material: Sequence[PlanMaterialPin] | None`; `build_payload` serializes it as an ordered list of exact `{role, canonical_id, material_fingerprint}` items. Keep schema identifier `plan_review_result_v2`: the field is optional/additive, pre-feature v2 readers ignore it, and rollback needs no migration. Idempotent reuse and progressive drift refresh retain their existing no-sidecar behavior, so they do not manufacture a new review-time baseline. On read, `sidecar.parse_reviewed_related_material` owns raw validation; an absent field alone is legacy-unpinned. This gives failed-sign recovery the related-material baseline actually reviewed without fabricating a certified attestation.\n- Edit `resign.py`: `resign_plan_review` does not call `compute_validity`, because its primary recovery case has no certified attestation. It retains its existing sidecar verdict and own-material-fingerprint guards, reads `reviewed_related_material`, and invokes `derive_plan_material_pin_health` on those records before signing. With enforcement enabled, stale drift, missing targets, or malformed records refuse re-sign; with enforcement disabled they remain advisory and re-sign proceeds. A pre-feature sidecar without records follows legacy-unpinned compatibility. Normal `sign_plan_review` still emits the complete current pin set as owned by child acaf.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Enabled pin drift invalidates the claim consumer.\n- [ ] Enabled pin drift prevents idempotent attestation reuse.\n- [ ] Enabled pin drift prevents progressive drift refresh.\n- [ ] Enabled pin drift in review-time sidecar records prevents re-sign.\n- [ ] Failed-sign recovery succeeds without an existing certified attestation when own material and review-time related material remain current.\n- [ ] Re-sign preserves the existing own-material staleness guard and never passes a sidecar payload to `compute_validity`.\n- [ ] Full LLM review threads the exact pre-LLM `review_snapshot.related_material` through `sidecar.emit` and `build_payload`; pre-feature sidecars behave as legacy-unpinned.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_plan_review_sidecar.py` proves a pre-feature sidecar reader ignores additive `reviewed_related_material` and otherwise behaves identically.\n- [ ] Derived health reports enabled pin drift as invalid.\n- [ ] Disabled enforcement reports the same drift as advisory without changing valid.\n- [ ] Legacy unpinned attestations remain valid across configuration toggles.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_plan_material_pin_config.py` proves unreadable optional enforcement configuration returns false and emits `plan_material_pin_config_unreadable` without raising.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_plan_material_pin_config.py` proves `sign_plan_review` emits identical complete pin lines with enforcement true and false, using the already-declared dependency on child acaf's emission path.\n- [ ] Missing, deleted, unreadable, or reducer-failing targets produce `stale-pin-missing`; non-missing read failures emit `plan_material_pin_target_unreadable` without raising.\n- [ ] Archived readable targets compare normally.\n- [ ] Duplicate role-plus-ID pins produce `malformed-pin`.\n- [ ] Re-enabling enforcement immediately invalidates existing drifted pins.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_attestation_invalidation.py` patches the ticket event writer and proves deriving advisory health makes zero writer calls.\n- [ ] Advisory health is returned in-band; child cb6b separately owns audit and UI surfacing.\n- [ ] `sidecar.parse_reviewed_related_material` returns `None` only for an absent field and maps every present-invalid variant to malformed/invalid without raising past a consumer boundary.\n- [ ] Sidecars remain `plan_review_result_v2`, and a pre-feature v2 reader ignores additive `reviewed_related_material`.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_drift_refresh_candidate.py` proves the full ticket state is passed to `compute_validity(DRIFT_REFRESH)`.\n- [ ] The same test proves signature, kind, reopen, registry, own-material, and pin validity are delegated.\n- [ ] The same test proves only dependency-hash drift qualification remains inline.\n- [ ] The same test proves reopened attestations are not progressive-refresh candidates.\n- [ ] `DEFAULT` preserves existing claim and reuse behavior when pins are current or legacy-unpinned.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_attestation_invalidation.py` directly proves `CLOSE` and `DRIFT_REFRESH` each disable only code freshness.\n- [ ] This story selects `DRIFT_REFRESH`; child 2bbd separately owns selecting `CLOSE` at close call sites.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_attestation_invalidation.py` proves existing plan-review validity keys retain their values with additive health.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_compute_validity_callers.py` uses an AST scan to prove every in-repo caller consumes mappings by named key and does not tuple-unpack or compare an exact result dict.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_attestation_invalidation.py` proves completion-verifier return shape remains unchanged.\n\n## Verification\n- Run focused attestation invalidation, reuse, drift-refresh, re-sign, sidecar compatibility, structured-config-warning, and config-golden tests.\n- Run `pytest -q tests/unit/test_attestation_invalidation.py tests/unit/test_plan_review_resign.py tests/unit/test_plan_review_sidecar.py tests/unit/test_drift_refresh_candidate.py tests/unit/test_plan_material_pin_config.py tests/unit/test_compute_validity_callers.py`.\n- Run `make check` and the non-integration test suite.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784549692477615001,"uuid":"d4cd3a79-6206-4724-92f8-da32ddacaaf9"}